1
00:00:03,031 --> 00:00:07,158
By January 1986, the space shuttle had flown 24 times.

2
00:00:08,120 --> 00:00:09,883
Each flight reinforced one idea.

3
00:00:09,923 --> 00:00:11,365
The system worked.

4
00:00:12,367 --> 00:00:15,712
Across those flights, engineers documented O-ring damage.

5
00:00:16,493 --> 00:00:20,922
Erosion, blow-by, hot gas pass seals designed to hold.

6
00:00:21,763 --> 00:00:24,448
Low-temperature flights all showed distress.

7
00:00:24,428 --> 00:00:28,074
But each flight survived, and the warning lost force.

8
00:00:29,155 --> 00:00:30,739
Danger became a known condition.

9
00:00:31,480 --> 00:00:33,382
A stop signal became a line item.

10
00:00:34,425 --> 00:00:37,951
The night before Challenger, engineers recommended against launch.

11
00:00:38,953 --> 00:00:39,975
The burden shifted.

12
00:00:40,034 --> 00:00:45,423
Instead of proving it safe to fly, they were asked to prove it was unsafe.

13
00:00:46,417 --> 00:00:52,088
On the coldest morning the program had ever faced, 73 seconds was all the physics needed.

14
00:00:52,149 --> 00:00:54,353
The warning was never missing.

15
00:00:55,295 --> 00:00:57,159
It had been made survivable for too long.

16
00:00:57,942 --> 00:01:00,527
Small causes, massive consequences.
